Thanks, if _ is allowed as the type, why are explicit types written at all?<p>Is the last example equivalent to<p><pre><code>    let (mut x, ref y, &z): (_, _, &_) = (1, 2, &3);
</code></pre>
and can we go even further<p><pre><code>    let (mut x, ref y, &z) = (1, 2, &3);
</code></pre>
If we can, when do we actually need specifying the types? To do the type conversion or what?<p>Probably because I don&#x27;t know Haskell (sorry) but I still imagine x y and z as names and even mut, ref and & as the &quot;access&quot; specifications, which define somehow the &quot;type&quot; of x y and z and not the type the thing accessed with the given name.
